WEBVTT

00:00:01.280 --> 00:00:04.560
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>to ventilate</i>?

00:00:04.640 --> 00:00:05.600
<v Student><b>Ventilar.</b>

00:00:05.600 --> 00:00:07.680
<v Teacher>Yeah. <b>Ventilación-ventilar</b>.

00:00:07.680 --> 00:00:09.520
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>to separate</i>?

00:00:10.980 --> 00:00:12.260
<v Student><b>Separar.</b>

00:00:12.260 --> 00:00:12.820
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:12.820 --> 00:00:13.860
<v Teacher><b>Separar.</b>

00:00:13.860 --> 00:00:19.780
<v Teacher>So in English what we pronounce as <i>separate</i>, maybe like an <i>e</i> sound, but if you look at how it's written, it's an <i>a</i>.

00:00:19.780 --> 00:00:20.660
<v Teacher><b>Separar.</b>

00:00:20.660 --> 00:00:21.540
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:21.320 --> 00:00:28.760
<v Teacher>So how was <i>to know</i>, something to do with <i>savvy</i>?

00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:29.420
<v Student><b>Saber.</b>

00:00:29.420 --> 00:00:30.200
<v Teacher><b>SaBer.</b>

00:00:30.200 --> 00:00:31.000
<v Student><b>Saber.</b>

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:31.740
<v Teacher>With a <i>b</i>.

00:00:31.740 --> 00:00:34.380
<v Teacher>Another way to remember this is <i>Homo sapien</i>,

00:00:34.380 --> 00:00:35.740
<v Teacher>there's that connection there.

00:00:35.740 --> 00:00:41.580
<v Teacher>The <i>Homo sapien</i> is the <i>wise creature</i>. Supposedly.

00:00:41.580 --> 00:00:43.740
<v Teacher>And how was <i>to come</i>?

00:00:45.020 --> 00:00:46.860
<v Teacher><i>Convenient</i>?

00:00:46.860 --> 00:00:47.660
<v Student><b>Venir.</b>

00:00:47.660 --> 00:00:48.380
<v Teacher><b>Venir.</b>

00:00:48.380 --> 00:00:48.780
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:48.780 --> 00:00:51.500
<v Teacher>So we can remember that <i>convenient</i> is "with coming",

00:00:51.500 --> 00:00:54.220
<v Teacher>when things come together, they are convenient.

00:00:54.120 --> 00:01:02.120
<v Teacher>We've seen the "to" forms of the verb end in <i>r</i> and the "I" forms most of the time end in <i>o</i>.

00:01:02.120 --> 00:01:05.320
<v Teacher>For example, <i>I want</i>, how was that?

00:01:06.140 --> 00:01:06.940
<v Student><b>Quiero.</b>

00:01:06.940 --> 00:01:07.500
<v Teacher><b>Quiero</b>.

00:01:07.500 --> 00:01:10.700
<v Teacher><i>I owe</i>? Which we can use like <i>must</i>:

00:01:10.700 --> 00:01:11.260
<v Student><b>Debo.</b>

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:12.460
<v Teacher><b>Debo</b>.

00:01:12.780 --> 00:01:14.460
<v Teacher><i>I try:</i>

00:01:15.460 --> 00:01:16.500
<v Student><b>Intento.</b>

00:01:16.500 --> 00:01:17.540
<v Teacher><b>Intento.</b>

00:01:17.540 --> 00:01:24.420
<v Teacher>Unless the verb is irregular, and we know some irregular verbs already. We saw <i>I am going</i>.

00:01:24.740 --> 00:01:25.380
<v Student><b>Voy.</b>

00:01:25.380 --> 00:01:25.780
<v Teacher><b>Voy.</b>

00:01:25.780 --> 00:01:28.100
<v Teacher>So that doesn't end in <i>o</i>, or in /o/.

00:01:28.100 --> 00:01:28.820
<v Teacher><b>Voy</b>.

00:01:28.820 --> 00:01:30.180
<v Teacher>It's an irregular verb.

00:01:30.180 --> 00:01:31.299
<v Teacher>So how does this work?

00:01:31.299 --> 00:01:37.460
<v Teacher>Now all "to" verbs, all verbs in the "to" form, when we say

00:01:38.080 --> 00:01:43.520
<v Teacher><i>to go</i>, <i>to want</i>, <i>to segregate</i>,

00:01:43.520 --> 00:01:46.080
<v Teacher>how would you say <i>to segregate</i>?

00:01:46.640 --> 00:01:50.720
<v Student><i>Segregation-</i><b>segregación-segregar</b>.

00:01:50.800 --> 00:01:51.760
<v Teacher>There you are.

00:01:51.760 --> 00:01:56.560
<v Teacher>All of them in the "to" form end in the letter <i>r</i>.

00:01:56.560 --> 00:01:58.720
<v Teacher>They either end in <i>-ar</i>,

00:01:59.560 --> 00:02:02.920
<v Teacher><i>-er</i>, or <i>-ir</i>.

00:02:02.920 --> 00:02:04.440
<v Teacher>We have an example of each.

00:02:04.440 --> 00:02:11.000
<v Teacher>We have like a thousand examples of the ones that end in <i>-ar</i> because this is the one that we're using to build these from,

00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:25.560
<v Teacher>for example, <i>simulation-</i><b>simulación-simular</b>. <i>Revelation-</i><b>revelación-revelar</b>. <i>Respiration-</i><b>respiración-respirar</b>. What do you think <b>respirar</b> means?

00:02:26.420 --> 00:02:27.300
<v Student><i>To breathe</i>.

00:02:27.300 --> 00:02:28.340
<v Teacher>Yes. <i>To breathe</i>.

00:02:28.340 --> 00:02:35.700
<v Teacher>So we could say <i>to respire</i> literally and we go, oh of course, this would be how I would say <i>breathe</i> in Spanish. <b>Respirar.</b> Good.

00:02:35.700 --> 00:02:39.060
<v Teacher>So we have many examples of <i>-ar</i> verbs.

00:02:39.260 --> 00:02:44.459
<v Teacher>We have one example of an <i>-er</i> verb, in its "to" form, which is <i>to know</i>.

00:02:44.459 --> 00:02:45.180
<v Teacher>How was that?

00:02:45.180 --> 00:02:46.620
<v Teacher><i>To know:</i>

00:02:46.620 --> 00:02:47.500
<v Student><b>Saber.</b>

00:02:47.500 --> 00:02:48.300
<v Teacher><b>Saber</b>.

00:02:48.300 --> 00:02:53.500
<v Teacher>And we have the example of the verb ending <i>-ir</i>, <i>ir</i>, which is <i>to come</i>.

00:02:53.780 --> 00:02:54.580
<v Student><b>Venir.</b>

00:02:54.580 --> 00:02:55.940
<v Teacher><b>Venir.</b> Good.

00:02:55.940 --> 00:03:03.860
<v Teacher>So all "to" forms are going to end in an <i>r</i>. And it's either going to be <i>-ar</i>, <i>-er</i>, or <i>-ir</i>.

00:03:03.260 --> 00:03:04.860
<v Teacher><i>a-r</i>, <i>e-r</i>, <i>i-r</i>.

00:03:04.860 --> 00:03:10.460
<v Teacher>In fact, and talking about "to" forms, it's actually with this "to" that we identify what is a verb.

00:03:10.460 --> 00:03:16.700
<v Teacher>Now it's good to talk about this because at school we learn that verbs are doing words,

00:03:17.120 --> 00:03:23.600
<v Teacher>which is really kind of unhelpful, because <i>to be</i> for example is, there's nothing, you're not doing anything.

00:03:23.600 --> 00:03:24.640
<v Teacher>If you say <i>is</i>,

00:03:25.340 --> 00:03:26.220
<v Teacher><i>he is here</i>,

00:03:26.220 --> 00:03:27.260
<v Teacher>what is he doing?

00:03:27.260 --> 00:03:28.460
<v Teacher>But <i>is</i> is a verb.

00:03:28.460 --> 00:03:30.700
<v Teacher><i>Is</i> is a verb because it comes from <i>to be</i>.

00:03:30.700 --> 00:03:32.620
<v Teacher>We don't say <i>He be here</i>.

00:03:32.620 --> 00:03:34.140
<v Teacher>We say <i>He is here</i>.

00:03:34.300 --> 00:03:39.580
<v Teacher>So the way we identify what is a verb, is that you can put <i>to</i> in front of it.

00:03:39.580 --> 00:03:41.660
<v Teacher><i>To be, to stay, to go</i>.

00:03:41.660 --> 00:03:42.620
<v Teacher>These are verbs.

00:03:42.620 --> 00:03:47.260
<v Teacher>And in Spanish, these are going to end in <i>r</i>. Either <i>-ar</i>, <i>-er</i>, or <i>-ir</i>.

00:03:48.180 --> 00:03:56.739
<v Teacher>Now the way we get the "I" version, is we take off this ending, we chop off this <i>-ar</i>, <i>-er</i>, or <i>-ir</i> and we put <i>-o</i>.

00:03:56.739 --> 00:03:58.019
<v Teacher>We have an example already.

00:03:58.180 --> 00:04:02.660
<v Teacher>We know how is <i>to try</i>. What was <i>to try</i>?

00:04:02.900 --> 00:04:03.940
<v Student><b>Intentar.</b>

00:04:03.940 --> 00:04:04.900
<v Teacher><b>Intentar.</b>

00:04:04.900 --> 00:04:05.780
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:05.780 --> 00:04:08.020
<v Teacher>And <i>I try:</i>

00:04:08.020 --> 00:04:08.900
<v Student><b>Intento.</b>

00:04:08.900 --> 00:04:09.700
<v Teacher><b>Intento.</b>

00:04:09.700 --> 00:04:10.020
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:10.020 --> 00:04:12.340
<v Teacher>So we take off <i>-ar</i> and we put on <i>-o</i>.

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:14.500
<v Teacher>But something else is happening as well.

00:04:14.580 --> 00:04:17.220
<v Teacher><b>Intentar</b>. <b>Intento.</b>

00:04:17.220 --> 00:04:18.980
<v Teacher>Good. The accent.

00:04:18.980 --> 00:04:21.060
<v Teacher><b>Intentar</b>, we have the accent on the end.

00:04:21.060 --> 00:04:23.940
<v Teacher>When we put the <i>-o</i>, the accent is just before it.

00:04:23.940 --> 00:04:24.740
<v Teacher><b>InTENto</b>.

00:04:24.740 --> 00:04:26.100
<v Teacher>Now this is extremely important.

00:04:26.100 --> 00:04:27.380
<v Teacher>If I say <b>intentO</b>,

00:04:28.060 --> 00:04:30.380
<v Teacher>if I put the accent on the end, it means something else.

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:31.740
<v Teacher>It means <i>he tried</i>.

00:04:31.740 --> 00:04:34.940
<v Teacher>Which is going to be useful for us later when we learn the past.

00:04:34.940 --> 00:04:42.780
<v Teacher>For now, we need to think that the accent in the present tense is going on the penultimate syllable. The second to last syllable.

00:04:43.060 --> 00:04:45.060
<v Teacher><b>Intentar</b> is not present tense.

00:04:45.060 --> 00:04:46.180
<v Teacher>It has no tense.

00:04:46.180 --> 00:04:48.500
<v Teacher>It's the "to" form. <i>To try</i>.

00:04:48.500 --> 00:04:55.060
<v Teacher>Part of the present tense, other than putting this <i>-o</i> for <i>I</i>, is also moving the accent:

00:04:55.060 --> 00:04:55.620
<v Teacher><b>intento</b>.

00:04:56.520 --> 00:04:59.240
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>to donate</i>?

00:04:59.800 --> 00:05:02.840
<v Student><i>Donation-</i><b>donación-donar</b>.

00:05:02.840 --> 00:05:03.320
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:03.320 --> 00:05:04.200
<v Teacher><b>Donar.</b>

00:05:04.200 --> 00:05:08.200
<v Teacher><i>I donate</i>. You take off the <i>-ar</i> and you put <i>-o</i>.

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:09.700
<v Student><b>Dono.</b>

00:05:09.700 --> 00:05:10.520
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:05:10.520 --> 00:05:11.320
<v Teacher><b>Dono</b>.

00:05:11.320 --> 00:05:14.600
<v Teacher><i>I don't donate</i> or <i>I'm not donating:</i>

00:05:14.600 --> 00:05:15.640
<v Student><b>No dono.</b>

00:05:15.640 --> 00:05:16.040
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:16.040 --> 00:05:17.480
<v Teacher><b>No dono</b>.

00:05:17.480 --> 00:05:20.120
<v Teacher>How was <i>to create</i>?

00:05:20.980 --> 00:05:21.700
<v Student><b>Crear.</b>

00:05:21.700 --> 00:05:22.300
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:22.300 --> 00:05:24.500
<v Teacher><b>Crear-creación-crear</b>.

00:05:24.500 --> 00:05:25.500
<v Teacher><i>I create:</i>

00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:26.300
<v Student><b>Creo.</b>

00:05:26.300 --> 00:05:28.980
<v Teacher><b>Creo</b>. Good.

00:05:31.260 --> 00:05:33.660
<v Teacher><b>Comer, comer</b> means <i>to eat</i>.

00:05:33.660 --> 00:05:36.540
<v Teacher>So how do you say <i>I eat</i> or <i>I'm eating</i>?

00:05:37.900 --> 00:05:38.700
<v Student><b>Como.</b>

00:05:38.700 --> 00:05:40.060
<v Teacher><b>Como</b>. Good.

00:05:40.060 --> 00:05:42.060
<v Teacher><i>I'm going to eat:</i>

00:05:42.640 --> 00:05:43.920
<v Student><b>Voy a comer.</b>

00:05:44.400 --> 00:05:46.320
<v Teacher><b>Voy a comer.</b>

00:05:46.320 --> 00:05:49.760
<v Teacher>The word for <i>late</i> in Spanish is <b>tarde</b>.

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:50.919
<v Teacher><b>Tarde</b>.

00:05:50.919 --> 00:05:56.680
<v Teacher>We know this from English as well because we have this slang in English, in British English at least,

00:05:56.680 --> 00:05:57.479
<v Teacher><i>tardy</i>.

00:05:57.479 --> 00:05:58.520
<v Teacher>Have you ever heard that?

00:05:58.520 --> 00:05:58.840
<v Student>Yes.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:05:59.800
<v Teacher><b>Tarde.</b>

00:05:59.800 --> 00:06:00.840
<v Teacher><b>Tarde.</b>

00:06:00.840 --> 00:06:03.240
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>I'm going to eat late</i>?

00:06:04.040 --> 00:06:06.040
<v Student><b>Voy a comer tarde.</b>

00:06:06.040 --> 00:06:06.440
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:06.440 --> 00:06:08.360
<v Teacher><b>Voy a comer tarde</b>.

00:06:08.360 --> 00:06:12.440
<v Teacher>You might have heard the word for <i>tomorrow</i> as well in Spanish.

00:06:12.440 --> 00:06:13.400
<v Teacher><b>Mañana</b>.

00:06:13.400 --> 00:06:17.160
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>I'm going to eat tomorrow</i>?

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:20.000
<v Student><b>Voy a comer mañana.</b>

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:22.320
<v Teacher><b>Voy a comer mañana.</b>

00:06:22.320 --> 00:06:31.360
<v Teacher>Now in Spanish, if you have some kind of future context, something that's showing you that you're talking about the future, you can just use the present.

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:40.419
<v Teacher>You can say <b>Voy a comer mañana</b> or you could just say <i>I eat tomorrow</i> because you have <i>tomorrow</i> showing you that you're talking about the future.

00:06:40.419 --> 00:06:43.620
<v Teacher>It's absolutely perfect Spanish, even though it sounds a bit odd in English.

00:06:43.600 --> 00:06:45.760
<v Teacher>It's perfect Spanish to say <i>I eat tomorrow</i>.

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:47.040
<v Teacher>There's no problem there.

00:06:47.040 --> 00:06:48.800
<v Teacher>So how would you say that?

00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:51.200
<v Student><b>Como mañana.</b>

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:52.560
<v Teacher><b>Como mañana.</b>

00:06:52.200 --> 00:07:01.400
<v Teacher>So if you want to say <i>I'm eating with Pablo tomorrow</i>. <i>I'm eating with Pablo tomorrow</i>. You just say <i>I eat with Pablo tomorrow</i>.

00:07:02.240 --> 00:07:04.000
<v Student>How do you say <i>with</i>?

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.320
<v Teacher>Do you remember how to say <i>to confirm</i>?

00:07:07.600 --> 00:07:09.520
<v Student><b>Confirmación-confirmar</b>.

00:07:09.520 --> 00:07:10.480
<v Teacher><i>Confirm</i>?

00:07:10.480 --> 00:07:12.640
<v Teacher>Good, and what did that mean literally?

00:07:12.639 --> 00:07:14.240
<v Student>Ah! "With signature".

00:07:14.240 --> 00:07:15.280
<v Teacher>So what is <i>with</i>?

00:07:15.280 --> 00:07:16.240
<v Student><b>Con firma</b>. <b>Con</b>.

00:07:16.240 --> 00:07:17.440
<v Teacher><b>Con.</b> Good.

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:18.080
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:17.440 --> 00:07:21.040
<v Teacher>So, <i>I'm eating with Pablo tomorrow:</i>

00:07:22.360 --> 00:07:25.000
<v Student><b>Como con Pablo mañana.</b>

00:07:25.000 --> 00:07:25.560
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:25.560 --> 00:07:27.560
<v Teacher><b>Como con Pablo mañana.</b>

00:07:27.560 --> 00:07:33.960
<v Teacher>So we can just use the present or we can say <i>I'm going to eat with Pablo tomorrow</i> and it's the same.

00:07:33.960 --> 00:07:38.120
<v Student><b>Voy a comer con Pablo mañana.</b>

00:07:38.120 --> 00:07:38.520
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:38.520 --> 00:07:41.080
<v Teacher><b>Voy a comer con Pablo mañana.</b>

00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:42.440
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:07:42.740 --> 00:07:52.420
<v Teacher>So we are taking off our ending. We're taking off our <i>-ar</i>, <i>-er</i> or <i>-ir</i> and we're adding <i>-o</i> to get the "I" version.

00:07:52.220 --> 00:08:00.460
<v Teacher>We are also accenting the penultimate syllable. The syllable that comes before the last.

00:08:00.460 --> 00:08:02.380
<v Teacher>What is <i>to organize</i>?

00:08:03.360 --> 00:08:06.800
<v Student><b>Organización-Organizar</b>.

00:08:06.800 --> 00:08:07.280
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:07.280 --> 00:08:11.680
<v Teacher>Now how do you say <i>I organize</i> or <i>I'm organizing</i>?

00:08:12.160 --> 00:08:13.440
<v Student><b>Organizo</b>?

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:14.560
<v Teacher><b>Organizo.</b>

00:08:14.560 --> 00:08:15.360
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:24.160
<v Teacher>I will just mention for anybody trying to keep up with the Spanish pronunciation that that <i>z</i> there is going to be pronounced /th/. /Organitho/ in Spain.

00:08:24.160 --> 00:08:25.360
<v Teacher><b>Organizo</b>.

00:08:25.880 --> 00:08:30.680
<v Teacher><i>To have</i> in Spanish is <b>tener</b>. <b>Tener.</b>

00:08:30.680 --> 00:08:31.479
<v Student><b>Tener.</b>

00:08:32.120 --> 00:08:34.919
<v Teacher>How do you say <i>I want to have it? I want to have it:</i>

00:08:34.919 --> 00:08:37.880
<v Student><b>Quiero tenerlo.</b>

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:40.760
<v Teacher>Good. <i>I'm going to have it:</i>

00:08:40.760 --> 00:08:43.000
<v Student><b>Voy a tenerlo.</b>

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:43.320
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:43.320 --> 00:08:46.440
<v Teacher><i>I'm going to have it late:</i>

00:08:46.440 --> 00:08:47.440
<v Student><b>Voy a tenerlo tarde.</b>

00:08:47.440 --> 00:08:48.720
<v Teacher>Good! <b>Voy a tenerlo tarde.</b>

00:08:51.839 --> 00:08:53.360
<v Teacher>If you want to say <i>later</i>,

00:08:53.400 --> 00:08:57.360
<v Teacher>and the word for <i>more</i> is <b>más</b>, <i>m-a-s</i>.

00:08:57.360 --> 00:08:58.100
<v Student><b>Más.</b>

00:08:58.440 --> 00:08:59.960
<v Teacher>Related to <i>massive</i>.

00:08:59.960 --> 00:09:02.360
<v Teacher>So how is <i>later</i>?

00:09:02.360 --> 00:09:03.720
<v Student><b>Más tarde.</b>

00:09:03.720 --> 00:09:04.680
<v Teacher><b>Más tarde.</b> Good.

00:09:04.680 --> 00:09:07.160
<v Teacher><i>I'm going to have it later:</i>

00:09:07.160 --> 00:09:10.699
<v Student><b>Voy a tenerlo más tarde.</b>

00:09:10.699 --> 00:09:11.500
<v Teacher>Good.

00:09:11.500 --> 00:09:14.139
<v Teacher>I will tell you something that's going to help you remember <b>tener</b>.

00:09:14.139 --> 00:09:17.500
<v Teacher><b>Tener</b> is a very interesting verb, because other than <i>to have</i>,

00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:21.300
<v Teacher>we can also translate it as <i>-tain</i>.

00:09:21.300 --> 00:09:23.540
<v Teacher><i>Contain</i> is <b>contener</b>.

00:09:23.540 --> 00:09:26.660
<v Teacher><i>Obtain</i>, this <i>-tain</i> is <b>tener</b>.

00:09:26.820 --> 00:09:30.100
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>obtain</i> in Spanish,

00:09:30.100 --> 00:09:33.540
<v Teacher>if <i>contain</i> becomes <b>contener</b>?

00:09:33.540 --> 00:09:34.420
<v Student><b>Obtener.</b>

00:09:34.420 --> 00:09:35.860
<v Teacher>Yes! <b>Obtener.</b>

00:09:35.860 --> 00:09:38.340
<v Teacher><i>Sustain</i>, this one changes a little bit.

00:09:38.340 --> 00:09:41.460
<v Teacher><i>Sus-</i>, which is <i>s-u-s</i>, becomes <i>s-o-s</i>

00:09:41.440 --> 00:09:43.600
<v Teacher>in Spanish.

00:09:43.600 --> 00:09:44.640
<v Student><b>Sostener.</b>

00:09:44.640 --> 00:09:45.760
<v Teacher><b>Sostener</b>.

00:09:45.760 --> 00:09:46.960
<v Teacher><i>Sustain</i>.

00:09:46.960 --> 00:09:48.000
<v Teacher><i>Maintain</i>.

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:48.640
<v Teacher><i>Maintain</i>,

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:51.760
<v Teacher>this <i>main</i> becomes <i>man-</i> in Spanish.

00:09:51.760 --> 00:09:53.760
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>maintain</i>?

00:09:54.839 --> 00:09:55.880
<v Student><b>Mantener.</b>

00:09:55.880 --> 00:09:56.680
<v Teacher><b>Mantener.</b>

00:09:56.680 --> 00:10:01.640
<v Teacher>And if you heard <b>entretener</b>, what would you think it means? <b>Entretener:</b>

00:10:02.380 --> 00:10:03.260
<v Student><i>Entertain.</i>

00:10:03.420 --> 00:10:03.740
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:10:03.740 --> 00:10:07.100
<v Teacher>So it changes a little bit, but you can recognize it.

00:10:07.100 --> 00:10:07.980
<v Teacher><b>Entretener</b>.

00:10:07.980 --> 00:10:10.220
<v Teacher>And <b>entre</b> in Spanish means <i>between</i>.

00:10:10.220 --> 00:10:14.380
<v Teacher>You might hear in Spanish <b>entre tu y yo</b>. <i>Between you and I</i>.

00:10:14.380 --> 00:10:16.360
<v Teacher><b>Entre tu y yo</b>.

00:10:16.360 --> 00:10:22.040
<v Teacher>Many languages express this idea of possession in different ways.

00:10:22.040 --> 00:10:26.680
<v Teacher>In English and in Spanish, we have a simple verb: <i>Have</i>, <b>tener</b>, to express possession.

00:10:27.060 --> 00:10:33.860
<v Teacher>But Arabic for example, you would say "at me" or "with me" instead of "I have."

00:10:33.860 --> 00:10:36.660
<v Teacher>So it's not a straightforward concept

00:10:36.459 --> 00:10:42.060
<v Teacher>that all languages express in the same way, this concept of possession.

00:10:42.060 --> 00:10:49.180
<v Teacher>In Turkish, for example, if you want to say "I have a car" you say "My car there is."

00:10:49.459 --> 00:10:56.820
<v Teacher>So it's not such a straightforward concept that we are expressing in all languages in the same way, this concept of possession.

00:10:56.820 --> 00:11:03.300
<v Teacher>Something that Spanish is alluding to here is kind of the symbiotic relationship in ownership.

00:11:03.020 --> 00:11:05.980
<v Teacher>When you own something, you also belong to it.

00:11:05.980 --> 00:11:09.900
<v Teacher>You must maintain it. You must sustain it. You must contain it.

00:11:09.900 --> 00:11:11.740
<v Teacher>It's a symbiotic relationship.

00:11:11.740 --> 00:11:14.860
<v Teacher>You don't just own things. You are also owned by them.

00:11:15.440 --> 00:11:19.120
<v Teacher><i>To have</i> is <b>tener</b>. And you also get these other verbs that you can use.

00:11:19.120 --> 00:11:24.320
<v Teacher><b>Obtener</b>, <b>contener</b>, <b>mantener</b>, <b>sostener</b>, <b>entretener</b>.

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:27.400
<v Teacher><i>I have</i> is <b>tengo</b>.

00:11:27.400 --> 00:11:28.680
<v Teacher>What happened here?

00:11:28.680 --> 00:11:31.080
<v Teacher>What should it be?

00:11:31.080 --> 00:11:31.880
<v Student><b>Teno.</b>

00:11:31.880 --> 00:11:33.160
<v Teacher>Yes. That's what it should be.

00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:34.600
<v Teacher>But it's irregular.

00:11:34.440 --> 00:11:35.880
<v Teacher>It has a <i>g</i> popping up.

00:11:35.880 --> 00:11:39.720
<v Teacher>But the nice thing about the irregular verbs in Spanish is that we can group them together.

00:11:39.720 --> 00:11:43.080
<v Teacher>There's always a little group of verbs that do things in the same way.

00:11:43.080 --> 00:11:45.800
<v Teacher>For example, what was <i>to come</i>?

00:11:46.580 --> 00:11:47.780
<v Student><b>Venir.</b>

00:11:47.780 --> 00:11:48.660
<v Teacher><b>Venir</b>. Very good.

00:11:48.660 --> 00:11:52.500
<v Teacher>Now <b>venir</b> behaves like <b>tener</b> when it makes the I form.

00:11:52.500 --> 00:11:56.580
<v Teacher>So if <b>tener</b> becomes <b>tengo</b>, <b>venir</b> might become…

00:11:57.980 --> 00:11:58.860
<v Student><b>Vengo.</b>

00:11:58.860 --> 00:11:59.740
<v Teacher><b>Vengo</b>!

00:11:59.740 --> 00:12:00.220
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:00.220 --> 00:12:01.980
<v Teacher>So <i>I come</i> is <b>vengo</b>.

00:12:01.980 --> 00:12:02.940
<v Teacher>It's irregular.

00:12:02.940 --> 00:12:07.819
<v Teacher>But we've already noticed two verbs that have this same pattern of irregularity.

00:12:07.819 --> 00:12:10.459
<v Teacher>And to think of them together helps us.

00:12:09.959 --> 00:12:18.120
<v Teacher>Now if you want to say <i>I will come tomorrow</i>, we don't know the word for <i>will</i>, but we don't need it. Because <i>tomorrow</i> is our future context.

00:12:18.120 --> 00:12:20.120
<v Teacher>What is the word for <i>tomorrow</i>?

00:12:20.360 --> 00:12:21.320
<v Student><b>Mañana</b>.

00:12:21.320 --> 00:12:21.720
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:21.720 --> 00:12:24.200
<v Teacher>So <i>I'm coming tomorrow:</i>

00:12:24.200 --> 00:12:25.240
<v Student><b>Vengo mañana.</b>

00:12:25.240 --> 00:12:26.440
<v Teacher><b>Vengo mañana.</b>

00:12:26.440 --> 00:12:28.200
<v Teacher>Very good.
